(
  'NCMEC 2025 — Child Sex Trafficking Reports Up 950%, AI-Generated CSAM Up 6,341%',
  'NCMEC documented a 950% surge in child sex trafficking reports in 2025 — from ~6,000 to 62,000+. AI-generated CSAM reports rose 6,341% — from 6,835 to 440,000+. Online enticement reports rose 77%. Financial sextortion rose 70%. These are federally mandated CyberTipline reports from online platforms, not estimates.',
  'The National Center for Missing and Exploited Children (NCMEC) operates the federally mandated CyberTipline — the legally required reporting mechanism by which online platforms must submit reports of child sexual exploitation material and activity. The 2025 annual data represents the largest documented spike in child exploitation reports in NCMEC''s history.

Documented 2025 data from NCMEC CyberTipline:
- Child sex trafficking reports: increased approximately 950% — from approximately 6,000 to over 62,000 reports
- AI-generated child sexual abuse material (CSAM) reports: increased 6,341% — from 6,835 to over 440,000 reports
- Online enticement reports: increased 77%
- Financial sextortion reports: increased 70%

These are CyberTipline submissions from online platforms — legally mandated reports under the PROTECT Our Children Act. They are not estimates, surveys, or extrapolations. Each report represents a platform''s submission of detected content or activity to the federal clearinghouse.

The 6,341% increase in AI-generated CSAM reflects the rapid deployment of image generation models capable of creating photorealistic child sexual abuse material without any victim. This category did not exist as a meaningful reporting category five years ago.

Department of Justice enforcement: On August 12, 2025, 11 defendants were charged in a federal indictment in the Central District of California alleging extensive sex trafficking of minors and young adults. The indictment is one of multiple federal enforcement actions in 2025, though enforcement capacity has not scaled proportionally with the reported increase in trafficking activity.',
