(
  'Epstein Files — 3 Million Pages Released, DEA Narcotics Probe, Maxwell Pleads Fifth',
  'The DOJ released over 3 million pages of Epstein files in January–February 2026. Revelations include a five-year DEA investigation targeting Epstein and 14 unnamed co-targets for narcotics-linked money transfers (redacted 69-page classified memo), an FBI network diagram, and a draft indictment never filed. Ghislaine Maxwell invoked the Fifth Amendment before House Oversight on February 9. Her attorney offered full testimony contingent on presidential clemency.',
  'The Department of Justice released over 3 million pages of documents related to Jeffrey Epstein through January and February 2026, representing the most comprehensive government document release related to the Epstein case since his 2019 arrest and death.

Key revelations from the released documents:

1. DEA Investigation: A previously undisclosed five-year Drug Enforcement Administration investigation targeting Epstein and 14 unnamed co-targets for suspicious financial transfers possibly linked to narcotics trafficking. The investigation is documented in a 69-page memo that remains classified; all co-targets are fully redacted. The investigation ran parallel to FBI investigations without apparent coordination with the federal prosecutors who ultimately declined to bring federal charges before the 2008 Florida non-prosecution agreement.

2. FBI Network Diagram: A previously undisclosed FBI visual network diagram mapping Epstein''s documented associates and financial relationships was included in the release. Specific names visible in the released version are partially redacted.

3. Draft Indictment Never Filed: Documents include a draft federal indictment that was prepared but never submitted. The charges and named defendants in the draft are partially redacted in the released version.

4. Ghislaine Maxwell — Fifth Amendment: Maxwell was subpoenaed to testify before the House Oversight Committee. On February 9, 2026, she invoked her Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination and declined to answer all substantive questions. Her attorney subsequently offered full congressional testimony contingent on a grant of presidential clemency from President Trump. Her attorney stated that Maxwell''s testimony would establish that both Trump and Clinton are "innocent of any wrongdoing" — a claim that cannot be independently evaluated given her refusal to testify.

Cross-reference: See Epstein Bank Settlements entry (financial-systems pillar) for $437M+ banking settlement data.',
