(
  'FISA Section 702 — Expires April 19, 2026: Clean Extension Threatened, Reform Stalled',
  'FISA Section 702 expires April 19, 2026. The White House is pushing a clean 18-month extension preserving warrantless access to Americans'' communications. FBI documented abuses include improper searches targeting racial justice protesters, political officials, campaign donors, and a state court judge. The bipartisan SAFE Act requiring warrants faces a difficult vote.',
  'Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA) Section 702 — the statutory authority under which the NSA, FBI, and CIA conduct warrantless surveillance of communications involving foreign persons that incidentally or deliberately capture Americans'' communications — expires April 19, 2026.

Legal framework: Section 702 allows collection of Americans'' communications without a warrant if one party to the communication is a foreign target, regardless of whether the American has done anything wrong. The collected communications are stored in databases that domestic law enforcement agencies including the FBI can subsequently search — also without a warrant — in what privacy advocates call a "backdoor search" loophole.

Documented FBI abuses under Section 702 (from FISC opinions and Inspector General reports):
- Improper warrantless searches of communications databases targeting racial justice protesters during 2020 demonstrations
- Improper searches targeting communications of political campaign officials and donors
- Improper search targeting a sitting state court judge
- FISC Judge Rudolph Contreras issued a formal finding of compliance failures; the FBI''s minimization procedures were found inadequate

White House position (February 2026): The administration is pushing for a "clean" 18-month extension with no additional warrant requirements or oversight mechanisms, arguing that adding warrant requirements would operationally impair counterterrorism and counterintelligence activities.

Senate response: Senator Dick Durbin stated during March 2026 Judiciary Committee proceedings: "We''ve been hearing these same excuses for over 20 years." A bipartisan coalition introduced the SAFE Act, which would require a warrant before FBI agents can search the Section 702 database for Americans'' communications. The bill faces resistance from intelligence community lobbying and administration opposition.',
