(
  'Alien.gov Registered — White House ''Stay Tuned,'' Pentagon UAP Files in Progress',
  'The White House formally registered alien.gov and aliens.gov through CISA in March 2026, following Trump''s February directive ordering DoD to identify and release UAP files. Neither domain is yet active. Secretary Hegseth confirmed Pentagon is working on disclosure. AARO caseload has exceeded 2,000 reports.',
  'In March 2026, the White House registered two new .gov domains through the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA): alien.gov and aliens.gov. Neither domain was active as of the March 2026 reporting period. White House Press Secretary Anna Kelly responded to media inquiries about the domain registrations with: "Stay tuned!"

Background and context:
- President Trump issued a formal directive in February 2026 ordering the Department of Defense to identify and prepare UAP (Unidentified Aerial Phenomena) files for release
- Secretary of Defense Pete Hegseth confirmed in a February 24, 2026 media appearance: "We''ve got our people working on it right now"
- The All-domain Anomaly Resolution Office (AARO) — the Pentagon''s official UAP investigation body — has exceeded 2,000 active case reports
- Former NASA Associate Administrator Michael Gold called the domain registrations "a significant achievement and milestone" in UAP disclosure progress
- DefenseScoop reported that the domains were registered through standard CISA .gov domain registration processes, consistent with official government web properties

Prior related entries: The prior entries "trump-directs-uap-file-release" and "defense-secretary-hegseth-confirms-pentagon-compliance" are superseded by this more current entry and should be archived or consolidated.

Status as of March 2026: No UAP files have been publicly released. The domain registrations represent an administrative step with no confirmed timeline for content publication.',
