(
  '3M PFAS Forever Chemicals — $10.5 Billion Settlement, Payments Flowing Through 2036',
  '3M is making payments on its $10.5–$12.5 billion PFAS settlement — the largest chemical contamination settlement in U.S. history — with public water utilities. Payments continue through 2036. PFAS do not break down in the body or environment and are linked to cancer, birth defects, and immune disruption. Utilities must file claims by July 31, 2026.',
  '3M Company has begun making payments under its $10.5–$12.5 billion PFAS (per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances) settlement with public water utilities across the United States — the largest chemical contamination settlement in U.S. history. Payments are structured over a 13-year period running through 2036.

PFAS chemistry: Per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances are a class of approximately 12,000 synthetic chemicals characterized by extremely strong carbon-fluorine bonds that do not break down in the environment or in human biological systems — earning them the designation "forever chemicals." PFAS compounds accumulate in soil, groundwater, drinking water systems, and human tissue over time. Peer-reviewed research links PFAS exposure to: multiple cancer types (kidney, testicular, bladder, thyroid, breast), birth defects and developmental disruption, immune system suppression, elevated cholesterol, and endocrine disruption.

Settlement scope and exclusions:
- The $10.5–$12.5 billion settlement covers public water utilities for water treatment costs related to PFAS contamination
- Utilities have until July 31, 2026 to file settlement claims
- The settlement does NOT cover: individual personal injury lawsuits (thousands pending separately), the New Jersey $450 million state-specific PFAS settlement (finalized May 2025), or ongoing litigation against DuPont, Chemours, and Corteva (spinoffs from DuPont''s PFAS chemical operations)

Corporate knowledge: Internal 3M documents produced in litigation revealed that 3M had internal knowledge of PFAS persistence and bioaccumulation properties as early as the 1950s — decades before the first public health warnings. The company continued manufacturing and marketing PFAS-containing products including Scotchgard and aqueous film-forming foam (AFFF, used by military and airport fire departments) through 2020, when it announced a phase-out.

The New Jersey settlement ($450M, May 2025) was secured by NJ Attorney General Matt Platkin and covers statewide PFAS contamination in New Jersey''s water systems specifically.',
